    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-10-04T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-10-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="639"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d639">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10395: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-04T14:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 4, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 4—6:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>444. Department’s 245, October 2, 3 p.m.—use of International Settlement Shanghai
                    as military base.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I called today on the Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs and made oral
                        representations leaving with him an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                        <note n="80" xml:id="d639fn80">
                            <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_378">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 378</ref>.</note> embodying all of
                        the points in paragraph number 4 of the Department’s telegram.</item>
                    <pb facs="0585" n="578" xml:id="pg_578"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The Vice Minister’s only comment was that the Chinese forces are
                        endangering Japanese lives and property in the International Settlement by
                        fire from Pootung and Chapei and that the Japanese have landed a very small
                        number of troops in the Settlement, their principal forces having been
                        disembarked elsewhere. The Foreign Office will report [<hi rend="italic"
                            >reply?</hi>] to our representations in due course.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>My British colleague will make similar representations to the Vice
                        Minister this afternoon as he is instructed to act on the same lines as
                        myself.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
